Effect of narratives on the HA listening experience

  • Data
  • Correlation of Sound Quality items
    • Time correlates with other items r=0.46 on average; other items correlate with other items r=0.71 on average.
  • Testing normality
    • Sound Quality composite and the standalone Time measure are non-normal. QuickSIN with all participants is non-normal; QuickSIN is normal after excluding three participants.
  • Sound Quality measure
    • Narratives do not affect Sound Quality.
    • ECHO does not interact with narratives to affect Sound Quality assessment.
    • Openness and Agreeableness interact with narratives to affect Sound Quality assessment.
    • Direction of change for Agreeableness x Narrative on Sound Quality
    • Effect sizes for Openness x Narrative and Agreeableness x Narrative
  • Time measure
    • Positive narrative leads to less time needed than Neutral & Negative narratives.
    • Narrative effect size for Time
    • ECHO does not interact with narrative condition to affect Time assessment.
    • Neuroticism interacts with narratives to affect Time assessment.
    • Direction of change for Neuroticism x Narrative on Time
    • Effect size for Neuroticism x Narrative
  • QuickSIN measure
    • QuickSIN scores are worse in Negative narrative than Positive.
    • Narrative effect size for QuickSIN
    • ECHO does not interact with narratives to affect QuickSIN.
    • BFI traits dont interact with narratives to affect QuickSIN.

Data

# convert variables from string into factors
data$ID <- as.factor(data$ID)
data$Framing.Condition <- factor(data$Framing.Condition, levels = c("Neutral", "Positive", "Negative"))

# Sound Quality composite score, excluding "time" item 
data$sq_average <- rowMeans(data[c(3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9, 11, 12, 13)], na.rm = TRUE)

# exclude QuickSIN datapoints less than 14; upper bound (Q3 + 1.5*IQR) is 14.5
data2 <- subset(data, QuickSIN < 14)

# split data by narrative condition to calculate positive- and negative-change scores
pos <- subset(data, Framing.Condition == "Positive")
neu <- subset(data, Framing.Condition == "Neutral")
neg <- subset(data, Framing.Condition == "Negative")
# note that BFI data is the same across narrative conditions, within the same participant
change_data <- data.frame(ID = pos$ID, 
                          pos_change_SQ = pos$sq_average - neu$sq_average, 
                          neg_change_SQ = neg$sq_average - neu$sq_average, 
                          pos_change_Time = pos$Time.Get.Used - neu$Time.Get.Used, 
                          neg_change_Time = neg$Time.Get.Used - neu$Time.Get.Used,
                          pos_change_QuickSIN = pos$QuickSIN - neu$QuickSIN, 
                          neg_change_QuickSIN = neg$QuickSIN - neu$QuickSIN,
                          BFI.Openness = pos$BFI.Openness, 
                          BFI.Agreeableness = pos$BFI.Agreeableness,
                          BFI.Neuroticism = pos$BFI.Neuroticism)

rm(list = c('pos', 'neu', 'neg'))

Time correlates with other items r=0.46 on average; other items correlate with other items r=0.71 on average.

Sound Quality composite and the standalone Time measure are non-normal. QuickSIN with all participants is non-normal; QuickSIN is normal after excluding three participants.

Sound Quality measure

Narratives do not affect Sound Quality.
# base model, only participant effects
m.base.SQ <- lmer(sq_average ~ (1|ID), data = data, REML=FALSE)

# model with narrative effect
m.narr.SQ <- lmer(sq_average ~ Framing.Condition + (1|ID), data = data, REML=FALSE)

# narrative condition doesn't improve the model for Sound Quality
anova(m.base.SQ, m.narr.SQ, test = "Chisq")
## Data: data

ECHO does not interact with narratives to affect Sound Quality assessment.
m2 <- lmer(sq_average ~ Framing.Condition + Echo.Global + (1|ID), data = data, REML=FALSE)
m3 <- lmer(sq_average ~ Framing.Condition*Echo.Global + (1|ID), data = data, REML=FALSE)

Openness and Agreeableness interact with narratives to affect Sound Quality assessment.
# BFI trait as fixed effect
m2.o <- lmer(sq_average ~ BFI.Openness + Framing.Condition + (1|ID), data = data, REML=FALSE)
m2.a <- lmer(sq_average ~ BFI.Agreeableness + Framing.Condition + (1|ID), data = data, REML=FALSE)
m2.n <- lmer(sq_average ~ BFI.Neuroticism + Framing.Condition + (1|ID), data = data, REML=FALSE)

# add BFI interaction term
m3.o <- lmer(sq_average ~ BFI.Openness*Framing.Condition + (1|ID), data = data, REML=FALSE)
m3.a <- lmer(sq_average ~ BFI.Agreeableness*Framing.Condition + (1|ID), data = data, REML=FALSE)
m3.n <- lmer(sq_average ~ BFI.Neuroticism*Framing.Condition + (1|ID), data = data, REML=FALSE)

Time measure

Positive narrative leads to less time needed than Neutral & Negative narratives.
# base model, participant effects only
m.base.Time <- lmer(Time.Get.Used ~ (1|ID), data = data, REML=FALSE)

# model with narrative effect
m.narr.Time <- lmer(Time.Get.Used ~ Framing.Condition + (1|ID), data = data, REML=FALSE)

# narrative condition improves the model for Time
anova(m.base.Time, m.narr.Time, test = "Chisq")
## Data: data
## Models:
## m.base.Time: Time.Get.Used ~ (1 | ID)
## m.narr.Time: Time.Get.Used ~ Framing.Condition + (1 | ID)

QuickSIN measure

QuickSIN scores are worse in Negative narrative than Positive.
# base model, participant effects only; excluding three participants with scores  14
m.base.QuickSIN <- lmer(QuickSIN ~ (1|ID), data = data2, REML=FALSE)

# model with narrative effect
m.narr.QuickSIN <- lmer(QuickSIN ~ Framing.Condition + (1|ID), data = data2, REML=FALSE)

# narrative condition improves the model for QuickSIN
